<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-09-25T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-09-25T18:00:00-05:00" n="502" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d502">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512 Flour/32: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-09-25T19:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">September 25,
                                        1928—7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>327. In order that Department may inform interested parties telegraph
                            whether flour tax at Canton reported in Canton despatch 715, August 15
                            to Legation<note n="72" xml:id="d502fn72">Not printed.</note> is
                            actually in force. Also whether Cunningham protested against flour tax
                            at Shanghai (see your 597, August 3, 6 p.m.) and result if any of
                            protest.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>